Major '''Edgar Oxenham Amm''' [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC & Bar]] (19 August 1898 &ndash; 25 March 1953) was a [[South Africa]]n aviator who served in World War I and became a [[flying ace]]; he was credited with ten aerial victories. He returned to service during World War II. Between the wars, and after World War II, he was a farmer and businessman.<ref>http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/safrica/amm.php Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref>

==Personal life==
Amm was born to Amy  Celia Hill and Edwin John Amm.<ref>http://www.1820settlers.com/modules.php?op=modload&name=Genealogy&file=getperson&personID=I41886&tree=1 Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref> He was their fourth child.<ref>http://www.1820settlers.com/modules.php?op=modload&name=Genealogy&file=familygroup&familyID=F13793&tree=1 Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref> He went from school to the army while still in South Africa, and voyaged to Britain in early 1918. After service in the Royal Air Force, he declined an opportunity to return home on the first flight ever from England to South Africa,<ref>http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1920/1920%20-%200346.html Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref> citing a promise to his father to never again fly. After he returned home, he farmed.<ref>http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/safrica/amm.php Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref>

Amm married Annie Joyce Peppercorn; they had two daughters and a son, all born in the 1930s.<ref>http://www.1820settlers.com/modules.php?op=modload&name=Genealogy&file=getperson&personID=I41886&tree=1 Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref> During World War II, Amm returned to service. After the war, he sold his farm and founded the South Coast Aviation Company. From there, he moved on to citrus farming, managing Valencia Estates at [[Letaba]].<ref>http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/safrica/amm.php Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref> His last known occupation was general manager of Tzaneen Co-operative Citrus Co Ltd, Politsi, [[Tzaneen]], Mpumalanga, South Africa.<ref>http://www.1820settlers.com/modules.php?op=modload&name=Genealogy&file=getperson&personID=I41886&tree=1 Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref>

==Military service==
Edgar O. Amm served in two World Wars. In the First, he was a lieutenant; in the Second, he was a major.<ref>http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/safrica/amm.php Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref>

===World War I===
Amm was seconded from the army to the Royal Air Force. He joined 29 Squadron in July 1918 as a [[Royal Aircraft Factory SE.5|SE.5]]a pilot. He was almost immediately successful, setting a German [[Fokker D.VII]] fighter afire on 12 August 1918. He amassed two more victories in August, two in September, three in October.<ref>http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/safrica/amm.php Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref> On 9 November, he drove down one Fokker D.VII and set another aflame. In turn, he was shot down by a third D.VII, but was unharmed.<ref>{{cite book |title= SE5/5a Aces of World War I |page= 73 }}</ref> He spent a very short spell as a prisoner of war; one version of his repatriation has him riding a bicycle into his old unit on 24 November;<ref>http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/safrica/amm.php Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref> another says he was in durance vile only 48 hours.<ref>{{cite book |title= SE5/5a Aces of World War I |page= 73 }}</ref>

A summary of Amm's victories credits him with seven enemy airplanes and an observation balloon destroyed, and two planes driven down out of control.<ref>http://www.theaerodrome.com/aces/safrica/amm.php Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref> His opportunity to fly home as part of the [[Silver Queen]] expedition would seem to show that he served well into 1919, and perhaps 1920, as the Queen didn't take off until 4 February 1920.<ref>http://www.prominentpeople.co.za/van-ryneveld-pierre.aspx Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref>

===World War II===
First, he was a flying instructor; then he served in Egypt and the Middle East, as well as Italy.<ref>{{cite book |title= SE5/5a Aces of World War I |page= 73 }}</ref>

==Death==
Amm died in a nursing home in Johannesburg on 25 March 1953. His death certificate showed him as ten years younger than his actual age.<ref>http://www.1820settlers.com/modules.php?op=modload&name=Genealogy&file=getperson&personID=I41886&tree=1 Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref>

==Honours and awards==
'''Distinguished Flying Cross (DFC)'''

Lieut. Edgar Oxenham Amm. (FRANCE)
   
A gallant and dashing airman who has destroyed four enemy machines and a balloon. On 17 September, in company with six other machines, this officer took part in an engagement with seventeen hostile aircraft; eight of these were destroyed, Lieut. Amm accounting for one. Supplement to the London Gazette, 3 December 1918<ref>http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/31046/supplements/14317 Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref><ref>http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/31046/supplements/14318 Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref>

Awarded a Bar in lieu of a second award of the Distinguished Flying Cross on 3 June 1919.<ref>http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/31378/supplements/7030 Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref>

Awarded the Belgian Croix de Guerre on 15 June 1919.<ref>http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/31457/supplements/8987 Retrieved 24 February 2010.</ref>

